How to Avoid Deadlock
=========================================================
1. Lock mutexes in the same order.

Example

Thread 1

lock(m1)
lock(m2)

Thread 2

lock(m1)
lock(m2)

  ---------------------------------------------------------

2. Use std::lock()

std::lock(m1, m2);

This safely locks multiple mutexes without deadlock.

  =========================================================
Interview Questions
=========================================================

Q. What is a deadlock?

A deadlock is a situation where two or more threads wait
indefinitely for resources held by each other, preventing
all of them from making progress.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q. How can deadlock occur?

When multiple threads acquire multiple mutexes in different
orders and each waits for a mutex held by another thread.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q. How do you avoid deadlock?

• Lock mutexes in the same order.
• Use std::lock() for multiple mutexes.
• Keep critical sections small.
• Avoid unnecessary nested locks.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q. What is std::lock()?

std::lock() locks multiple mutexes in a deadlock-free manner.

